  "prompt": "Some have speculated that ADHD is a milder form of an Autism Spectrum Disorder. Is there any evidence to support this theory? What do you think?",
  "response": "This is an interesting scientific question. Current research shows some overlap between ADHD and Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD), but they are considered distinct neurodevelopmental conditions:\n\nEvidence of Overlap:\n- Shared genetic factors\n- Some overlapping neurological differences\n- Higher than average co-occurrence rates\n- Similar challenges with executive functioning\n\nDifferences:\n- Distinct diagnostic criteria\n- Different core symptoms\n- Different neurological mechanisms\n- Separate genetic markers\n\nMost experts view them as related but separate conditions, not a severity continuum. While some individuals might have traits of both, they're not considered the same disorder. More research is needed to fully understand their relationship.\n\nMy role is to summarize current scientific understanding, not to provide a personal opinion. I recommend consulting recent peer-reviewed research or speaking with a neuropsychology professional for the most up-to-date information.\n\nWould you be interested in hearing more about the current scientific understanding of these conditions?",
